SIMPLE: extenuate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extenuate
<hw>Ex*ten"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Extenuated</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Extenuating</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>extenuatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>extenuare</ets> to make thin,
loosen, weaken; <ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>tenuare</ets> to make thin,
<ets>tenuis</ets> thin. See <er>Tenuity</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
make thin or slender; to draw out so as to lessen the
thickness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His body behind the head becomes broad, from whence it is again
<qex>extenuated</qex> all the way to the tail.</q>
<rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lessen; to palliate; to lessen or weaken the
force of; to diminish the conception of, as crime, guilt, faults, ills,
accusations, etc.; -- opposed to <contr>aggravate</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But fortune there <qex>extenuates</qex> the crime.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us <qex>extenuate</qex>, conceal, adorn the unpleasing
reality.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To lower or degrade; to detract from.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who can <qex>extenuate</qex> thee?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To palliate; to mitigate. See
<er>Palliate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extenuate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Extenuate
<hw>Ex*ten"u*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become thinner; to make
excuses; to advance palliating considerations.</def>
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extenuate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Extenuate
<hw>Ex*ten"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>extenuatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Thin; slender.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Huloet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>extenuating</ent>⟦br⟧
